    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-04-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-04-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="339"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d339">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 24074/4.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Calhoun</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-04-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 22, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Calhoun, referring to legation’s April 15, says Mr. Baugh<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d339fn1">Vice and deputy consul general at Hankow.</note> reported
                    under date of April 20 that Hunan situation had not improved; that it was feared
                    the trouble would spread, and that he had telegraphed Americans to return
                    immediately to Hankow.</p>
                <p>Mr. Calhoun says further that he requested Rear Admiral Hubbard on 17th to
                    dispose of naval forces so as to render assistance if necessary, and that he
                    [Hubbard] reported the sailing of the <hi rend="italic">Cleveland</hi> for
                    Hankow on the 18th to be followed as soon as possible by other vessels.</p>
            </div>
